President Biden addressed the public from FEMA Headquarters in Washington, D.C. regarding the preparations and response to Hurricane Ida, which made landfall in Louisiana. He expressed the seriousness of the storm and urged people to listen to instructions from local and state officials. The President assured that the country's full resources will be dedicated to rescue and recovery efforts once the storm passes. He highlighted the extensive preparation and pre-positioning of resources, including meals, water, generators, and search and rescue teams. The President emphasized the need for caution and support for those affected by the hurricane. He also mentioned signing emergency declarations for Louisiana and Mississippi and coordinating with governors and other officials in the region. The President concluded by acknowledging the challenges ahead and the importance of community support.